{'slug': 'maungatere', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Maungatere was banded at Temple Basin Ski field in August 2017 with the help of Forest, the ski field manager. In this photo Maungatere is puffed up, trying to look as big as possible which is thought to be an aggressive or defensive behaviour. He is now often seen around Arthur's Pass Village.

Pegasus Bay School sponsored and named Maungatere after a visit and talk to the school from the Kea Sighting Project.

Maungatere is a significant place for the school. "This is the name of our local Maunga (mountain) and what our learning community is named after. Maungatere signifies aspiring to reach for the top and to always try your best."

Maungatere was treated for lead poisoning in May 2019 and then released into the Hawdon valley.', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Pegasus Bay School', 'sponsor_website': 'http://www.pegasusbay.school.nz/Home/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite-crop-c0-53__0-38-500x500-70.jpeg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite-crop-c0-53__0-38-350x250-70.jpeg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite.jpeg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Mark Brabyn'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black 7 on White', 'name': 'Maungatere', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2537', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:35.579585+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-02-21T08:37:35+13:00'}

{'slug': 'phillip', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Phillip is named after one of the local DOC rangers who worked along the Milford Highway during the summer of 2018/2019. Phillip writes poetry and wrote a special poem for our kea work while we were banding these birds...

THE BANDED KEA

The kea ventured down from the low mound,
to where cast-about food is commonly found.
to get about warily on the flat ground,
a hippity hop and sometimes a bound.

Waiting around patiently, was a lass with a noose,
her strings were all set and the loop was all loose.
A hesitant step inside the carefully laid line,
a quick tug of the rope and ‘you are all mine’

The kea jumped into the air - quite high,
and issued a squawk, and then tried to fly.
Tension on the line and back down with a thump,
an undignified landing on a green feathered rump.

Before she had time to get over the fright,
she was grabbed from behind and gathered up tight.
She went all floppy and pretended to be meek, 
but for the unwary, she attacked with her beak.

A pretty coloured bracelet- just above the claw,
not put on too tightly, in case it goes raw.
She was banded and blooded and ID’d as a bird,
and all throughout this, barely a peep was heard.

Measured and weighed and plucked like a duck,
an extra feather or two, just for good luck.
Time now to release her, back to her own kind,
a few more to catch, but first we must find. 

Many things harm the birds, including old lead,
food given with love, but not what should be fed.
Kea have to be monitored, this is an absolute must, 
thanks to the efforts of the Kea Conservation Trust.

You too can help, with donations and time,
but whatever you do, remember this rhyme.
Bad food will hurt them, as will a loss of their home,
if you see them abused, give us a call on your phone.

Phillip Robertson.
DoC Ranger - Fiordland
March ‘19', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Junwei Ho'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Fiordland', 'band_combo': 'Yellow A on Black', 'name': 'Phillip', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2119', 'date_modified': '2019-04-22T12:27:54.174203+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-22T12:28:02+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project.

{'slug': 'phillip', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Phillip is named after one of the local DOC rangers who worked along the Milford Highway during the summer of 2018/2019. Phillip writes poetry and wrote a special poem for our kea work while we were banding these birds...

THE BANDED KEA

The kea ventured down from the low mound,
to where cast-about food is commonly found.
to get about warily on the flat ground,
a hippity hop and sometimes a bound.

Waiting around patiently, was a lass with a noose,
her strings were all set and the loop was all loose.
A hesitant step inside the carefully laid line,
a quick tug of the rope and ‘you are all mine’

The kea jumped into the air - quite high,
and issued a squawk, and then tried to fly.
Tension on the line and back down with a thump,
an undignified landing on a green feathered rump.

Before she had time to get over the fright,
she was grabbed from behind and gathered up tight.
She went all floppy and pretended to be meek, 
but for the unwary, she attacked with her beak.

A pretty coloured bracelet- just above the claw,
not put on too tightly, in case it goes raw.
She was banded and blooded and ID’d as a bird,
and all throughout this, barely a peep was heard.

Measured and weighed and plucked like a duck,
an extra feather or two, just for good luck.
Time now to release her, back to her own kind,
a few more to catch, but first we must find. 

Many things harm the birds, including old lead,
food given with love, but not what should be fed.
Kea have to be monitored, this is an absolute must, 
thanks to the efforts of the Kea Conservation Trust.

You too can help, with donations and time,
but whatever you do, remember this rhyme.
Bad food will hurt them, as will a loss of their home,
if you see them abused, give us a call on your phone.

Phillip Robertson.
DoC Ranger - Fiordland
March ‘19', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Junwei Ho'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Fiordland', 'band_combo': 'Yellow A on Black', 'name': 'Phillip', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2119', 'date_modified': '2019-04-22T12:27:54.174203+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-22T12:28:02+12:00'}

{'slug': 'phillip', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Phillip is named after one of the local DOC rangers who worked along the Milford Highway during the summer of 2018/2019. Phillip writes poetry and wrote a special poem for our kea work while we were banding these birds...

THE BANDED KEA

The kea ventured down from the low mound,
to where cast-about food is commonly found.
to get about warily on the flat ground,
a hippity hop and sometimes a bound.

Waiting around patiently, was a lass with a noose,
her strings were all set and the loop was all loose.
A hesitant step inside the carefully laid line,
a quick tug of the rope and ‘you are all mine’

The kea jumped into the air - quite high,
and issued a squawk, and then tried to fly.
Tension on the line and back down with a thump,
an undignified landing on a green feathered rump.

Before she had time to get over the fright,
she was grabbed from behind and gathered up tight.
She went all floppy and pretended to be meek, 
but for the unwary, she attacked with her beak.

A pretty coloured bracelet- just above the claw,
not put on too tightly, in case it goes raw.
She was banded and blooded and ID’d as a bird,
and all throughout this, barely a peep was heard.

Measured and weighed and plucked like a duck,
an extra feather or two, just for good luck.
Time now to release her, back to her own kind,
a few more to catch, but first we must find. 

Many things harm the birds, including old lead,
food given with love, but not what should be fed.
Kea have to be monitored, this is an absolute must, 
thanks to the efforts of the Kea Conservation Trust.

You too can help, with donations and time,
but whatever you do, remember this rhyme.
Bad food will hurt them, as will a loss of their home,
if you see them abused, give us a call on your phone.

Phillip Robertson.
DoC Ranger - Fiordland
March ‘19', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Junwei Ho'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Fiordland', 'band_combo': 'Yellow A on Black', 'name': 'Phillip', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2119', 'date_modified': '2019-04-22T12:27:54.174203+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-22T12:28:02+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'matty', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "'Matty' is named after the a young chap from Newcastle, England, that we hauled out of the White Horse Hill campground to come and help us when we caught three kea in one go! He helped us move the kea to a comfortable, dry area for banding, passed us our gear and took notes for us.\r\n\r\nA lot of kea research went on in the area until about ten years ago. Researchers from Vienna, Austria spent a lot of time around Aoraki observing kea to gain a better understanding of their behavioural biology. Several PhD students from the University of Canterbury also spent time in the area researching the then reasonably plentiful kea population. Not a lot has happened since but hopefully things are about to change! With the beginnings of the kea sighting project kicking off in other areas where kea and humans interact, and the Kea Conservation Trust's lead removal project, there will be more work happening here. Watch this space.", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/matty/Matty_Aoraki-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/matty/Matty_Aoraki-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/matty/Matty_Aoraki.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Cam Mulvey'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Aoraki', 'band_combo': 'Black J on Grey', 'name': 'Matty', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-1440', 'date_modified': '2019-04-17T14:14:17.923720+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-17T14:14:17+12:00'}

{'slug': 'phillip', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Phillip is named after one of the local DOC rangers who worked along the Milford Highway during the summer of 2018/2019. Phillip writes poetry and wrote a special poem for our kea work while we were banding these birds...

THE BANDED KEA

The kea ventured down from the low mound,
to where cast-about food is commonly found.
to get about warily on the flat ground,
a hippity hop and sometimes a bound.

Waiting around patiently, was a lass with a noose,
her strings were all set and the loop was all loose.
A hesitant step inside the carefully laid line,
a quick tug of the rope and ‘you are all mine’

The kea jumped into the air - quite high,
and issued a squawk, and then tried to fly.
Tension on the line and back down with a thump,
an undignified landing on a green feathered rump.

Before she had time to get over the fright,
she was grabbed from behind and gathered up tight.
She went all floppy and pretended to be meek, 
but for the unwary, she attacked with her beak.

A pretty coloured bracelet- just above the claw,
not put on too tightly, in case it goes raw.
She was banded and blooded and ID’d as a bird,
and all throughout this, barely a peep was heard.

Measured and weighed and plucked like a duck,
an extra feather or two, just for good luck.
Time now to release her, back to her own kind,
a few more to catch, but first we must find. 

Many things harm the birds, including old lead,
food given with love, but not what should be fed.
Kea have to be monitored, this is an absolute must, 
thanks to the efforts of the Kea Conservation Trust.

You too can help, with donations and time,
but whatever you do, remember this rhyme.
Bad food will hurt them, as will a loss of their home,
if you see them abused, give us a call on your phone.

Phillip Robertson.
DoC Ranger - Fiordland
March ‘19', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Junwei Ho'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Fiordland', 'band_combo': 'Yellow A on Black', 'name': 'Phillip', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2119', 'date_modified': '2019-04-22T12:27:54.174203+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-22T12:28:02+12:00'}

{'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project. 

In 1923, Captain Ernest Valentine Sanderson founded the 'New Zealand Native Bird Protection Society', which in 1935 was renamed 'Forest and Bird Protection Society of New Zealand'.

Fast-forward to this day and Forest & Bird continues to flourish as one of New Zealand's strongest conservation organisations.

Unsurprisingly, Forest & Bird North Canterbury thought 'Captain Sanderson' was a fitting name for a kea!

Captain Sanderson is affectionately co-sponsored by Jordan Manek and Amanda Jill following an unforgettable encounter with this kea in Arthur's Pass that sparked an immense and lasting appreciation for the clowns of the mountains.", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Forest & Bird (North Canterbury)', 'sponsor_website': 'http://forestandbird.org.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/captain-sanderson/Captain_Sanderson-crop-c0-58__0-5-500x500-70.JPG', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/captain-sanderson/Captain_Sanderson-crop-c0-58__0-5-350x250-70.JPG', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/captain-sanderson/Captain_Sanderson.JPG'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Amanda Jill'}, 'get_age': 5, 'get_life_stage': 'Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White T on Green', 'name': 'Captain Sanderson', 'birthday': '2014-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-1517', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:24.891201+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-06-28T00:21:18+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'maungatere', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Maungatere was banded at Temple Basin Ski field in August 2017 with the help of Forest, the ski field manager. {'slug': 'carlos', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Carlos was banded in June 2018 as a fledgling in Arthur's Pass by Mark and Kate.

The Villa Maria students wrote the following about the kea they sponsored:

We named our kea Carlos because the name means King (of Spain) as well as manly, strong, funny, cute and nice. 10M from Villa Maria (2018) has been learning about Aotearoa's land and it's animals which lead us to talk about kea. To raise this money we did a Jellybean Raffle for a week with $1 per entry. While doing this project we learnt the following about kea.
- Kea are extremely intelligent birds.
- Kea are endemic to New Zealand and are the world's only alpine parrot.
- Kea are very sociable and cheeky birds and often referred to as the "clown of the mountains"
- The kea used to be on the New Zealand $10 note from 1967 to 1992 but was replaced by the whio in 1992.

We hope you find our bird amazing and help support the 'Kea Sightings Project.'', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Villa Maria College', 'sponsor_website': 'http://www.villa.school.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/carlos/Carlos2-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.JPG', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/carlos/Carlos2-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.JPG', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/carlos/Carlos2.JPG'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Mark Brabyn'}, 'get_age': 1, 'get_life_stage': 'Juvenile', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White S on Blue', 'name': 'Carlos', 'birthday': '2018-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2182', 'date_modified': '2018-08-21T17:01:45.514823+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-08-21T16:58:11+12:00'}

{'slug': 'sharlotte', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Female', 'bird_extended': {'description': "UPDATE - April 1st 2019:
Unfortunately Sharlotte the kea has been found to have VERY high blood lead levels. Please keep an eye out for her if you're near Homer Tunnel or anywhere in the Milford Sound area of Fiordland. Please contact us or DOC Te Anau if you see her so she can be caught and treated for lead poisoning. She will be released again into the wild once she is healthy (usually after a few weeks).

This kea, banded at Homer Tunnel in March 2019, is named after the late Sharlotte Stainsby who was in the DOC partnership team in Dunedin for many years. Sadly Sharlotte passed away early 2018 at 41 years young. One of Sharlotte’s very last trips was to Fiordland where she visited Doubtful Sound. Sharlotte was stoic with a dry sense of humour and a determination of kea proportions.

{'slug': 'theo-ii', 'status': 'Dead', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "'Theo II' is named after the first mokopuna (grandchild) of Pete and Fi Neale, hard working, conservation-minded locals from Arthur's Pass. They have been huge supporters, sponsors and helpers right from the start of this project and have previously named two other kea that were banded in Arthur's Pass village. It has been a little disheartening, however, because these birds have not been sighted in the village again. This is actually a good thing - it means that they have most likely dispersed away into the mountains, to a better spot where they don't face the danger of humans and our food and cars etc each and every day.

The 'problem' that we have is that young kea often disperse away from the site where you first encounter them and they may never be seen again. However, the beauty and value of the Kea Sightings Database is that citizen scientists everywhere, i.e. YOU, have spotted and reported seeing kea that were banded ten or more years ago, while out in remote valleys, far away from the sites where they were first seen. So if you see Theo II or any of his mates out there, please keep reporting them! The information we are learning is extremely valuable.

UPDATE: April 24 2019
Theo II has died. He was hit by a car at Deaths Corner and brought into the DOC Visitor Centre at Arthur's Pass. Please take care around kea with your vehicle.", 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': "Arthur's Pass Alpine Motels", 'sponsor_website': 'https://arthurs-pass-alpine-motels.business.site/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/theo-ii/Theo_II_and_friends-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/theo-ii/Theo_II_and_friends-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/theo-ii/Theo_II_and_friends.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Laura Young'}, 'get_age': None, 'get_life_stage': None, 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black II on White', 'name': 'Theo II', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2967', 'date_modified': '2019-04-25T22:35:19.878037+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-17T23:19:07+12:00'}

{'slug': 'kerewa', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Kerewa (meaning clever) was banded as a fledgling in the Arthur's Pass township in 2017.

Update: 29th November 2017
In October 2017, Kerewa was caught and taken in for treatment at the South Island Wildlife Hospital for lead poisoning. Kerewa has had several weeks of chelation treatment before being declared "lead-free" and has now been released near Arthur's Pass. 

Kerewa has been in good company - his buddy Wananga was also in for lead poisoning treatment. They were looked after exceptionally well by the amazing team at the South Island Wildlife Hospital in Christchurch getting lots of stimulation and activity during their stay. 

Please keep an eye out for Kerewa and Wānanga and report any sightings into the sightings database so we can keep track of how they're doing post-treatment.

The Arthur's Pass community is working on removing lead from key buildings in Arthur's Pass village where kea eat the lead (which tastes sweet to them) and accumulates in their body. Hopefully in a few more years, no more kea will need to be treated for lead poisoining. If you wish to donate to this lead removal project, please contact the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust or the Kea Conservation Trust to make a donation.', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Canterbury Environmental Trust', 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kerewa/24210176_718361335027821_4636913317455997510_o-crop-c0-39__0-53-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kerewa/24210176_718361335027821_4636913317455997510_o-crop-c0-39__0-53-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/kerewa/24210176_718361335027821_4636913317455997510_o.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'South Island Wildlife Hospital'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Red J on White', 'name': 'Kerewa', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-1632', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:33.321802+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:14+12:00'}

{'slug': 'rasputin', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "'Rasputin' was named by a good friend of our team who sometimes helps us out with our work while in Arthur's Pass. 

Named after Grigori Rasputin from Russia who led a fascinating existence including having significant influence on the Tsar and his family at the time, a self-proclaimed mystic, visionary, prophet and a religious charlatan, perhaps?

Apart from being a memorable name, Rasputin's life may well reflect that of some individual kea.. a bit of a wanderer, having sway and leaving a big impression on people. Throw in some trickery, allure them with mystique. Some see them both as disreputable peasants! They are both certainly characters which people have mixed feelings about. 

Food for thought: Was their historical influence actually so profound or has their impact and reputation been disproportionately subject to major embellishment as time's gone by? (Think kea sheep-killing days).", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/rasputin/kea_spread_wing_Clio_Reid-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/rasputin/kea_spread_wing_Clio_Reid-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/rasputin/kea_spread_wing_Clio_Reid.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Clio Reid'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White 6 on Orange', 'name': 'Rasputin', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2658', 'date_modified': '2019-04-17T22:20:39.566528+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-17T22:20:28+12:00'}

{'slug': 'phillip', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Phillip is named after one of the local DOC rangers who worked along the Milford Highway during the summer of 2018/2019. Phillip writes poetry and wrote a special poem for our kea work while we were banding these birds...

THE BANDED KEA

The kea ventured down from the low mound,
to where cast-about food is commonly found.
to get about warily on the flat ground,
a hippity hop and sometimes a bound.

Waiting around patiently, was a lass with a noose,
her strings were all set and the loop was all loose.
A hesitant step inside the carefully laid line,
a quick tug of the rope and ‘you are all mine’

The kea jumped into the air - quite high,
and issued a squawk, and then tried to fly.
Tension on the line and back down with a thump,
an undignified landing on a green feathered rump.

Before she had time to get over the fright,
she was grabbed from behind and gathered up tight.
She went all floppy and pretended to be meek, 
but for the unwary, she attacked with her beak.

A pretty coloured bracelet- just above the claw,
not put on too tightly, in case it goes raw.
She was banded and blooded and ID’d as a bird,
and all throughout this, barely a peep was heard.

Measured and weighed and plucked like a duck,
an extra feather or two, just for good luck.
Time now to release her, back to her own kind,
a few more to catch, but first we must find. 

Many things harm the birds, including old lead,
food given with love, but not what should be fed.
Kea have to be monitored, this is an absolute must, 
thanks to the efforts of the Kea Conservation Trust.

You too can help, with donations and time,
but whatever you do, remember this rhyme.
Bad food will hurt them, as will a loss of their home,
if you see them abused, give us a call on your phone.

Phillip Robertson.
DoC Ranger - Fiordland
March ‘19', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Junwei Ho'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Fiordland', 'band_combo': 'Yellow A on Black', 'name': 'Phillip', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2119', 'date_modified': '2019-04-22T12:27:54.174203+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-22T12:28:02+12:00'}

{'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project.

{'slug': 'theo-ii', 'status': 'Dead', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "'Theo II' is named after the first mokopuna (grandchild) of Pete and Fi Neale, hard working, conservation-minded locals from Arthur's Pass. They have been huge supporters, sponsors and helpers right from the start of this project and have previously named two other kea that were banded in Arthur's Pass village. It has been a little disheartening, however, because these birds have not been sighted in the village again. This is actually a good thing - it means that they have most likely dispersed away into the mountains, to a better spot where they don't face the danger of humans and our food and cars etc each and every day.

The 'problem' that we have is that young kea often disperse away from the site where you first encounter them and they may never be seen again. However, the beauty and value of the Kea Sightings Database is that citizen scientists everywhere, i.e. YOU, have spotted and reported seeing kea that were banded ten or more years ago, while out in remote valleys, far away from the sites where they were first seen. So if you see Theo II or any of his mates out there, please keep reporting them! The information we are learning is extremely valuable.

UPDATE: April 24 2019
Theo II has died. He was hit by a car at Deaths Corner and brought into the DOC Visitor Centre at Arthur's Pass. {'slug': 'phillip', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Phillip is named after one of the local DOC rangers who worked along the Milford Highway during the summer of 2018/2019. Phillip writes poetry and wrote a special poem for our kea work while we were banding these birds...

THE BANDED KEA

The kea ventured down from the low mound,
to where cast-about food is commonly found.
to get about warily on the flat ground,
a hippity hop and sometimes a bound.

Waiting around patiently, was a lass with a noose,
her strings were all set and the loop was all loose.
A hesitant step inside the carefully laid line,
a quick tug of the rope and ‘you are all mine’

The kea jumped into the air - quite high,
and issued a squawk, and then tried to fly.
Tension on the line and back down with a thump,
an undignified landing on a green feathered rump.

Before she had time to get over the fright,
she was grabbed from behind and gathered up tight.
She went all floppy and pretended to be meek, 
but for the unwary, she attacked with her beak.

A pretty coloured bracelet- just above the claw,
not put on too tightly, in case it goes raw.
She was banded and blooded and ID’d as a bird,
and all throughout this, barely a peep was heard.

Measured and weighed and plucked like a duck,
an extra feather or two, just for good luck.
Time now to release her, back to her own kind,
a few more to catch, but first we must find. 

Many things harm the birds, including old lead,
food given with love, but not what should be fed.
Kea have to be monitored, this is an absolute must, 
thanks to the efforts of the Kea Conservation Trust.

You too can help, with donations and time,
but whatever you do, remember this rhyme.
Bad food will hurt them, as will a loss of their home,
if you see them abused, give us a call on your phone.

Phillip Robertson.
DoC Ranger - Fiordland
March ‘19', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/phillip/Phillip_-_Monkey_Creek_-_Junwei_Ho.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Junwei Ho'}, 'get_age': 0, 'get_life_stage': 'Fledgling', 'study_area': 'Fiordland', 'band_combo': 'Yellow A on Black', 'name': 'Phillip', 'birthday': '2019-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2119', 'date_modified': '2019-04-22T12:27:54.174203+12:00', 'date_imported': '2019-04-22T12:28:02+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'makimaki', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Makimaki is often seen being rather aggressive towards visitors on the Milford Road, particularly near Homer Tunnel. {'slug': 'matty', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "'Matty' is named after the a young chap from Newcastle, England, that we hauled out of the White Horse Hill campground to come and help us when we caught three kea in one go! He helped us move the kea to a comfortable, dry area for banding, passed us our gear and took notes for us.\r\n\r\nA lot of kea research went on in the area until about ten years ago. Researchers from Vienna, Austria spent a lot of time around Aoraki observing kea to gain a better understanding of their behavioural biology. Several PhD students from the University of Canterbury also spent time in the area researching the then reasonably plentiful kea population. Not a lot has happened since but hopefully things are about to change! With the beginnings of the kea sighting project kicking off in other areas where kea and humans interact, and the Kea Conservation Trust's lead removal project, there will be more work happening here. {'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. {'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. {'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project.

{'slug': 'wananga', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Update: 29th November 2017
In October 2017, Wānanga was caught and taken in for treatment at the South Island Wildlife Hospital for lead poisoning. Wānanga has had several weeks of chelation treatment before being declared "lead-free" and has now been released near Arthur's Pass. 

Wānanga has been in good company - his buddy Kerewa was also in for lead poisoning treatment. They were looked after exceptionally well by the amazing team at the South Island Wildlife Hospital in Christchurch getting lots of stimulation and activity during their stay. 

Please keep an eye out for Wānanga and Kerewa and report any sightings into the sightings database so we can keep track of how they're doing post-treatment.

The Arthur's Pass community is working on removing lead from key buildings in Arthur's Pass village where kea eat the lead (which tastes sweet to them) and accumulates in their body. Hopefully in a few more years, no more kea will need to be treated for lead poisoining. If you wish to donate to this lead removal project, please contact the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust or the Kea Conservation Trust to make a donation. 

Wānanga was banded at Death's Corner by Corey Mosen in April 2017. His Māori name 'Wānanga' translates to: instructor, wise person, sage, authority, expert, guru, philosopher, savant.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/wananga/Wananga-crop-c0-41__0-49-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/wananga/Wananga-crop-c0-41__0-49-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/wananga/Wananga.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': None}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White D on Blue', 'name': 'Wananga', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2590', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:43.566346+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-06-28T00:21:37.587267+12:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'jesse', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Jesse can often be found investigating Deaths Corner or Candy's Bend.

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. {'slug': 'maungatere', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Maungatere was banded at Temple Basin Ski field in August 2017 with the help of Forest, the ski field manager. In this photo Maungatere is puffed up, trying to look as big as possible which is thought to be an aggressive or defensive behaviour. He is now often seen around Arthur's Pass Village.

Pegasus Bay School sponsored and named Maungatere after a visit and talk to the school from the Kea Sighting Project.

Maungatere is a significant place for the school. "This is the name of our local Maunga (mountain) and what our learning community is named after. Maungatere signifies aspiring to reach for the top and to always try your best."

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'kester', 'status': 'Dead', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "This cheeky little fella is often seen with a bunch of others around the village. 

This kea is named after Kester—a boy who lives in Arthur's Pass village, in fact one of only four children that live there! Kester's mum and dad are highly active in conservation, are members of the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust and dedicate a lot of their time to trapping, weeding and APWT admin. They come and help out with kea conservation work whenever they can and Kester and his brother Asher (who also has a kea named after him) are learning all about kea conservation in their spare time. 

Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust play a significant role in kea conservation and advocacy work as well as working hard to protect a range of other species.

Update: November 7th 2018 - Kester was found dead at Temple Basin. He probably died as a result of a high-speed mid air collision with something. He was tested for lead (Pb) poisoning in September and was found to have extremely high lead levels in his system. Lead has numerous physiological impacts on kea, just as it does in humans (e.g. slow response times, impaired neurological function and more) which suggests his ability to respond to dangers in his environment could well have been compromised.", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': "Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust", 'sponsor_website': 'http://apwt.org.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Laura Young'}, 'get_age': None, 'get_life_stage': None, 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black S on Pink', 'name': 'Kester', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2235', 'date_modified': '2019-08-18T01:52:45.865242+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-11-07T11:18:09+13:00'}

{'slug': 'kester', 'status': 'Dead', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "This cheeky little fella is often seen with a bunch of others around the village. 

This kea is named after Kester—a boy who lives in Arthur's Pass village, in fact one of only four children that live there! Kester's mum and dad are highly active in conservation, are members of the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust and dedicate a lot of their time to trapping, weeding and APWT admin. They come and help out with kea conservation work whenever they can and Kester and his brother Asher (who also has a kea named after him) are learning all about kea conservation in their spare time. 

Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust play a significant role in kea conservation and advocacy work as well as working hard to protect a range of other species.

Update: November 7th 2018 - Kester was found dead at Temple Basin. He probably died as a result of a high-speed mid air collision with something. He was tested for lead (Pb) poisoning in September and was found to have extremely high lead levels in his system. Lead has numerous physiological impacts on kea, just as it does in humans (e.g. slow response times, impaired neurological function and more) which suggests his ability to respond to dangers in his environment could well have been compromised.", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': "Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust", 'sponsor_website': 'http://apwt.org.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Laura Young'}, 'get_age': None, 'get_life_stage': None, 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black S on Pink', 'name': 'Kester', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2235', 'date_modified': '2019-08-18T01:52:45.865242+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-11-07T11:18:09+13:00'}

{'slug': 'tuhura', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Tuhura (meaning "explore") was banded at Deaths Corner in April 2017 as a fledgling. Valarie, Jane Goodall and Hopey were all banded at a similar time to Tuhura and some of them are likely to be his siblings.

Tuhura's name was chosen after a naming poll by Active Adventures who are one of the major sponsors of this project. 

Update August/September 2018: Wondering why Tuhura  - one of the most highly sighted kea - hasn't been seen for a while? He spends a lot of his time in the carpark overlooking the Otira Viaduct. In late August, he was hit by a car or had some sort of collision accident in the carpark and was found by the team looking very concussed, injured and worse for wear. We took him into the South Island Wildlife Hospital straight away and he has been treated by the wonderful team there. He has had to have eye surgery and now one eye has been removed. We'll provide more information as it comes to light.

Update: October 2018: Tuhura is back! After amazing treatment by Dr Pauline and team after his accident, Tuhura was released back into the wild in mid October. He has regularly been seen by visitors and seems to be coping well with his missing eye, compensating in other ways. Please take special care around this bird as his responses are still compromised as he gets used to living with just one eye.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': 'Active Adventures', 'sponsor_website': 'http://activeadventures.com/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/tuhura/tuhura2-crop-c0-45__0-28-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/tuhura/tuhura2.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'George Moon'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Yellow G on Black', 'name': 'Tuhura', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2561', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:42.640362+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-08-04T17:36:42+12:00'}

{'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project. 

In 1923, Captain Ernest Valentine Sanderson founded the 'New Zealand Native Bird Protection Society', which in 1935 was renamed 'Forest and Bird Protection Society of New Zealand'.

Fast-forward to this day and Forest & Bird continues to flourish as one of New Zealand's strongest conservation organisations.

Unsurprisingly, Forest & Bird North Canterbury thought 'Captain Sanderson' was a fitting name for a kea!

Captain Sanderson is affectionately co-sponsored by Jordan Manek and Amanda Jill following an unforgettable encounter with this kea in Arthur's Pass that sparked an immense and lasting appreciation for the clowns of the mountains.", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Forest & Bird (North Canterbury)', 'sponsor_website': 'http://forestandbird.org.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/captain-sanderson/Captain_Sanderson-crop-c0-58__0-5-500x500-70.JPG', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/captain-sanderson/Captain_Sanderson-crop-c0-58__0-5-350x250-70.JPG', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/captain-sanderson/Captain_Sanderson.JPG'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Amanda Jill'}, 'get_age': 5, 'get_life_stage': 'Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White T on Green', 'name': 'Captain Sanderson', 'birthday': '2014-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-1517', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:24.891201+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-06-28T00:21:18+12:00'}

{'slug': 'wananga', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Update: 29th November 2017
In October 2017, Wānanga was caught and taken in for treatment at the South Island Wildlife Hospital for lead poisoning. Wānanga has had several weeks of chelation treatment before being declared "lead-free" and has now been released near Arthur's Pass. 

Wānanga has been in good company - his buddy Kerewa was also in for lead poisoning treatment. They were looked after exceptionally well by the amazing team at the South Island Wildlife Hospital in Christchurch getting lots of stimulation and activity during their stay. 

Please keep an eye out for Wānanga and Kerewa and report any sightings into the sightings database so we can keep track of how they're doing post-treatment.

The Arthur's Pass community is working on removing lead from key buildings in Arthur's Pass village where kea eat the lead (which tastes sweet to them) and accumulates in their body. Hopefully in a few more years, no more kea will need to be treated for lead poisoining. If you wish to donate to this lead removal project, please contact the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust or the Kea Conservation Trust to make a donation. 

Wānanga was banded at Death's Corner by Corey Mosen in April 2017. His Māori name 'Wānanga' translates to: instructor, wise person, sage, authority, expert, guru, philosopher, savant.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/wananga/Wananga-crop-c0-41__0-49-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/wananga/Wananga-crop-c0-41__0-49-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/wananga/Wananga.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': None}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White D on Blue', 'name': 'Wananga', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2590', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:43.566346+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-06-28T00:21:37.587267+12:00'}

{'slug': 'spark', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Spark was banded in Arthur's Pass township by Mark and Kate in October 2017 as a fledgling.

{'slug': 'wananga', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Update: 29th November 2017
In October 2017, Wānanga was caught and taken in for treatment at the South Island Wildlife Hospital for lead poisoning. Wānanga has had several weeks of chelation treatment before being declared "lead-free" and has now been released near Arthur's Pass. 

Wānanga has been in good company - his buddy Kerewa was also in for lead poisoning treatment. They were looked after exceptionally well by the amazing team at the South Island Wildlife Hospital in Christchurch getting lots of stimulation and activity during their stay. 

Please keep an eye out for Wānanga and Kerewa and report any sightings into the sightings database so we can keep track of how they're doing post-treatment.

The Arthur's Pass community is working on removing lead from key buildings in Arthur's Pass village where kea eat the lead (which tastes sweet to them) and accumulates in their body. Hopefully in a few more years, no more kea will need to be treated for lead poisoining. If you wish to donate to this lead removal project, please contact the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust or the Kea Conservation Trust to make a donation. 

Wānanga was banded at Death's Corner by Corey Mosen in April 2017. His Māori name 'Wānanga' translates to: instructor, wise person, sage, authority, expert, guru, philosopher, savant.', 'is_featured': True, 'sponsor_name': None, 'sponsor_website': None, 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/wananga/Wananga-crop-c0-41__0-49-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/wananga/Wananga-crop-c0-41__0-49-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/wananga/Wananga.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': None}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White D on Blue', 'name': 'Wananga', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2590', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:43.566346+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-06-28T00:21:37.587267+12:00'}

{'slug': 'kester', 'status': 'Dead', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "This cheeky little fella is often seen with a bunch of others around the village. 

This kea is named after Kester—a boy who lives in Arthur's Pass village, in fact one of only four children that live there! Kester's mum and dad are highly active in conservation, are members of the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust and dedicate a lot of their time to trapping, weeding and APWT admin. They come and help out with kea conservation work whenever they can and Kester and his brother Asher (who also has a kea named after him) are learning all about kea conservation in their spare time. 

Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust play a significant role in kea conservation and advocacy work as well as working hard to protect a range of other species.

Update: November 7th 2018 - Kester was found dead at Temple Basin. He probably died as a result of a high-speed mid air collision with something. He was tested for lead (Pb) poisoning in September and was found to have extremely high lead levels in his system. Lead has numerous physiological impacts on kea, just as it does in humans (e.g. slow response times, impaired neurological function and more) which suggests his ability to respond to dangers in his environment could well have been compromised.", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': "Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust", 'sponsor_website': 'http://apwt.org.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018-crop-c0-5__0-5-500x500-70.jpg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018-crop-c0-5__0-5-350x250-70.jpg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/kester/Kester_AP_Oct_1_2018.jpg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Laura Young'}, 'get_age': None, 'get_life_stage': None, 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black S on Pink', 'name': 'Kester', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2235', 'date_modified': '2019-08-18T01:52:45.865242+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-11-07T11:18:09+13:00'}

{'slug': 'maungatere', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Maungatere was banded at Temple Basin Ski field in August 2017 with the help of Forest, the ski field manager. In this photo Maungatere is puffed up, trying to look as big as possible which is thought to be an aggressive or defensive behaviour. He is now often seen around Arthur's Pass Village.

Pegasus Bay School sponsored and named Maungatere after a visit and talk to the school from the Kea Sighting Project.

Maungatere is a significant place for the school. "This is the name of our local Maunga (mountain) and what our learning community is named after. Maungatere signifies aspiring to reach for the top and to always try your best."

Maungatere was treated for lead poisoning in May 2019 and then released into the Hawdon valley.', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Pegasus Bay School', 'sponsor_website': 'http://www.pegasusbay.school.nz/Home/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite-crop-c0-53__0-38-500x500-70.jpeg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite-crop-c0-53__0-38-350x250-70.jpeg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite.jpeg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Mark Brabyn'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black 7 on White', 'name': 'Maungatere', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2537', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:35.579585+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-02-21T08:37:35+13:00'}

{'slug': 'maungatere', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Maungatere was banded at Temple Basin Ski field in August 2017 with the help of Forest, the ski field manager. In this photo Maungatere is puffed up, trying to look as big as possible which is thought to be an aggressive or defensive behaviour. He is now often seen around Arthur's Pass Village.

Pegasus Bay School sponsored and named Maungatere after a visit and talk to the school from the Kea Sighting Project.

Maungatere is a significant place for the school. "This is the name of our local Maunga (mountain) and what our learning community is named after. Maungatere signifies aspiring to reach for the top and to always try your best."

Maungatere was treated for lead poisoning in May 2019 and then released into the Hawdon valley.', 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Pegasus Bay School', 'sponsor_website': 'http://www.pegasusbay.school.nz/Home/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite-crop-c0-53__0-38-500x500-70.jpeg', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite-crop-c0-53__0-38-350x250-70.jpeg', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/maungatere/Black7onWhite.jpeg'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Mark Brabyn'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'Black 7 on White', 'name': 'Maungatere', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2537', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:35.579585+12:00', 'date_imported': '2018-02-21T08:37:35+13:00'}

{'slug': 'spark', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Spark was banded in Arthur's Pass township by Mark and Kate in October 2017 as a fledgling.
In 2017 alone, three kea (including Simon and Andrew) were electrocuted at Temple Basin skifield from chewing on wires.  This has also been a problem in other mountain villages such as Mt Cook. There intelligence and curiosity can be their downfall. The Department of Conservation have worked with Orion to hopefully sort out this issue. 

Andrew Docking from Smart Connections named and sponsored Spark after finding out about the project  after staying a night at Hawdon hut with some of the Arthur's Pass Kea Team.

Hopefully Spark wont be jinxed by his name!!", 'is_featured': False, 'sponsor_name': 'Smart Connections', 'sponsor_website': 'http://www.smartconnections.co.nz/', 'profile_picture': {'large': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/spark/Spark-crop-c0-28__0-26-500x500-70.JPG', 'thumbnail': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/__sized__/birds/spark/Spark-crop-c0-28__0-26-350x250-70.JPG', 'full_size': 'https://media.keadatabase.nz/media/birds/spark/Spark.JPG'}, 'profile_picture_attribution': 'Mark Brabyn'}, 'get_age': 2, 'get_life_stage': 'Sub-Adult', 'study_area': 'Waimakariri', 'band_combo': 'White Z on Brown', 'name': 'Spark', 'birthday': '2017-01-01', 'primary_band': 'V-2522', 'date_modified': '2018-04-04T11:00:41.165165+12:00', 'date_imported': '2017-10-24T18:56:09+13:00'}

{'slug': 'wananga', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': 'Update: 29th November 2017
In October 2017, Wānanga was caught and taken in for treatment at the South Island Wildlife Hospital for lead poisoning. Wānanga has had several weeks of chelation treatment before being declared "lead-free" and has now been released near Arthur's Pass. 

Wānanga has been in good company - his buddy Kerewa was also in for lead poisoning treatment. They were looked after exceptionally well by the amazing team at the South Island Wildlife Hospital in Christchurch getting lots of stimulation and activity during their stay. 

Please keep an eye out for Wānanga and Kerewa and report any sightings into the sightings database so we can keep track of how they're doing post-treatment.

The Arthur's Pass community is working on removing lead from key buildings in Arthur's Pass village where kea eat the lead (which tastes sweet to them) and accumulates in their body. Hopefully in a few more years, no more kea will need to be treated for lead poisoining. If you wish to donate to this lead removal project, please contact the Arthur's Pass Wildlife Trust or the Kea Conservation Trust to make a donation. 

Wānanga was banded at Death's Corner by Corey Mosen in April 2017. {'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project. 

In 1923, Captain Ernest Valentine Sanderson founded the 'New Zealand Native Bird Protection Society', which in 1935 was renamed 'Forest and Bird Protection Society of New Zealand'.

Fast-forward to this day and Forest & Bird continues to flourish as one of New Zealand's strongest conservation organisations.

Unsurprisingly, Forest & Bird North Canterbury thought 'Captain Sanderson' was a fitting name for a kea!

{'slug': 'captain-sanderson', 'status': 'Alive', 'sex': 'Male', 'bird_extended': {'description': "Captain Sanderson was banded as a sub-adult in Arthur's Pass township in October 2016 by Laura Young and Mark Brabyn, the founders of the Kea Sighting Project.
